<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
	<title> First JavaScript</title>
	<style>
		button{
			border-radius: 8px;
		}
		#js,#hello{
			float: right;
			background-color: powderblue;
		}
		#demo,#date{
			background-color: coral;
		}
		img,#close{
			margin-left: 370px;
		}
		#demo1,#demo2{
			display: none;
		}
	</style>
	<script>
window.alert('alert javascript');//You can skip window keyword & only write alert(). You can use an alert box to display data.
function display() {
  document.getElementById("demo1").style.display="block";
  document.getElementById("demo2").style.display="block";
} 
function hide() {
  document.getElementById("demo1").style.display="none";
  document.getElementById("demo2").style.display="none";
}
</script>
</head>
<body>
<h1>My First Javascript</h1>
<button type="button"
onclick="document.getElementById('demo').innerHTML = Date()" id="date">Display Date and Time.</button>
<p id="demo"></p>
<button type="button" onclick="document.getElementById('js').innerHTML='Hello !! JavaScript'" id="hello">Click me!</button><br>
<p id="js"></p>
<br>
<hr><br>
In this case JavaScript changes the value of the src (source) attribute of an image.<br>
<img src="https://external-content.duckduckgo.com/iu/?u=http%3A%2F%2Fclipart-library.com%2Fimg%2F1943967.jpg&f=1&nofb=1" width="340px" height="280px" id="door"><br>
<button type="button" onclick="document.getElementById('door').src='https://external-content.duckduckgo.com/iu/?u=http%3A%2F%2Fclipart-library.com%2Fimg%2F1943967.jpg&f=1&nofb=1'" id="close">Close Door</button>
<button type="button" onclick="document.getElementById('door').src='https://external-content.duckduckgo.com/iu/?u=https%3A%2F%2Ftse1.mm.bing.net%2Fth%3Fid%3DOIP.wAd0tu4giubyyZ494S50vgAAAA%26pid%3DApi&f=1'" id="open">Open Door</button>
<!--till here was internal script, now will write external script.--><br>

<p id="demo1">Hello Dolly!</p>
<p id="demo2">How are you?</p>
<button type="button" onclick="display()">Display hidden</button>
<button type="button" onclick="hide()">Display none</button><br>

<br>Click on print button to print the page. <button onclick="window.print()">Print</button><!--the window.print() method in the browser to print the content of the current window.-->
